{"action": "input", "code": "def color_between_same_color_pixels(grid: np.ndarray, line_color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a line color, this function colors all black pixels between two pixels of the same color in the same row or column.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. line_color: int - An integer representing the color of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in range(10):\n        if color != black and color != line_color:\n            for i in range(grid.shape[0]):\n                row = grid[i, :]\n                col = grid[:, i]\n                color_pixels = np.where(row == color)[0]\n                if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                    for j in range(len(color_pixels) - 1):\n                        start = color_pixels[j]\n                        end = color_pixels[j + 1]\n                        if np.all(row[start + 1:end] == black):\n                            row[start + 1:end] = color\n                color_pixels = np.where(col == color)[0]\n                if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                    for j in range(len(color_pixels) - 1):\n                        start = color_pixels[j]\n                        end = color_pixels[j + 1]\n                        if np.all(col[start + 1:end] == black):\n                            col[start + 1:end] = color\n    return grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    line = find_color(input_grid)\n    out = color_between_same_color_pixels(copy)\n    return out\ndef find_color(grid: np.ndarray, index: int) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and an index, this function returns the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. index: int - An integer representing the index of the row or column.\n    \n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it.\n    \"\"\"\n    row = grid[index, :]\n    col = grid[:, index]\n    unique_row = np.unique(row)\n    unique_col = np.unique(col)\n    if len(unique_row) == 1:\n        return unique_row[0]\n    elif len(unique_col) == 1:\n        return unique_col[0]\n    else:\n        return -1", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    line = `find the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it`(input_grid)\n    out = `For any not black and not line color, if 2 pixels in the color are in same row or column, color all black pixels between them in the color`(copy)\n    return out", "gpt_code": "def color_between_same_color_pixels(grid: np.ndarray, line_color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a line color, this function colors all black pixels between two pixels of the same color in the same row or column.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. line_color: int - An integer representing the color of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in range(10):\n        if color != black and color != line_color:\n            for i in range(grid.shape[0]):\n                row = grid[i, :]\n                col = grid[:, i]\n                color_pixels = np.where(row == color)[0]\n                if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                    for j in range(len(color_pixels) - 1):\n                        start = color_pixels[j]\n                        end = color_pixels[j + 1]\n                        if np.all(row[start + 1:end] == black):\n                            row[start + 1:end] = color\n                color_pixels = np.where(col == color)[0]\n                if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                    for j in range(len(color_pixels) - 1):\n                        start = color_pixels[j]\n                        end = color_pixels[j + 1]\n                        if np.all(col[start + 1:end] == black):\n                            col[start + 1:end] = color\n    return grid\ndef find_color(grid: np.ndarray, index: int) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and an index, this function returns the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. index: int - An integer representing the index of the row or column.\n    \n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it.\n    \"\"\"\n    row = grid[index, :]\n    col = grid[:, index]\n    unique_row = np.unique(row)\n    unique_col = np.unique(col)\n    if len(unique_row) == 1:\n        return unique_row[0]\n    elif len(unique_col) == 1:\n        return unique_col[0]\n    else:\n        return -1", "holes": {"color_between_same_color_pixels": "For any not black and not line color, if 2 pixels in the color are in same row or column, color all black pixels between them in the color", "find_color": "find the color which pixels in a whole row or column are in it"}}
