{"action": "edit", "code": "def color_between_same_color_pixels(grid: np.ndarray, line_color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a line color, this function finds all pixels in the grid that have the same color as the line color and \n    turns all black pixels between any two pixels of the same color in the same row or column into the line color.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. line_color: int - An integer representing the color of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in range(10):\n        if color != black and color != line_color:\n            for i in range(grid.shape[0]):\n                row = grid[i, :]\n                col = grid[:, i]\n                black_pixels = []\n                color_pixels = []\n                for j in range(grid.shape[1]):\n                    if row[j] == black:\n                        black_pixels.append(j)\n                    elif row[j] == color:\n                        color_pixels.append(j)\n                        if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                            for k in range(color_pixels[-2] + 1, color_pixels[-1]):\n                                grid[i, k] = color\n                            black_pixels = []\n                            color_pixels.pop(0)\n                black_pixels = []\n                color_pixels = []\n                for j in range(grid.shape[0]):\n                    if col[j] == black:\n                        black_pixels.append(j)\n                    elif col[j] == color:\n                        color_pixels.append(j)\n                        if len(color_pixels) > 1:\n                            for k in range(color_pixels[-2] + 1, color_pixels[-1]):\n                                grid[k, i] = color\n                            black_pixels = []\n                            color_pixels.pop(0)\n    return grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    line = find_color(input_grid)\n    out = color_between_same_color_pixels(input_grid, line)\n    return out\ndef find_color(grid: np.ndarray) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid, this function finds the color of the line in the grid.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    An integer representing the color of the line.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in range(10):\n        if color != black:\n            for i in range(grid.shape[0]):\n                row = grid[i, :]\n                col = grid[:, i]\n                if np.all(row == color) or np.all(col == color):\n                    return color\n    return black", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:                                                                                                                                           \n    line = find_color(input_grid)                                                                                                                                                         \n    out = color_between_same_color_pixels(input_grid, line)                                                                                                                                           \n    return out", "gpt_code": "def color_between_same_color_pixels(grid: np.ndarray, line_color: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a grid and a line color, this function finds all pixels in the grid that have the same color as the line color and \n    turns all black pixels between any two pixels of the same color in the same row or column into the line color.\n    \n    Args:\n    1. grid: np.ndarray - A numpy array representing the input grid.\n    2. line_color: int - An integer representing the color of the line.\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the updated grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    for color in range(10):\n        if color != black and col